      "content": "The 2016 Permanent Court of Arbitration (PCA) ruling in the South China Sea case actually found that China’s claims in most of the Spratly Islands are not supported by UNCLOS, and it explicitly rejected China’s “nine-dash line” as a legal basis for sovereignty. This means the ruling does not validate China’s assertions as a whole, but rather confirms that only a portion of China’s claims have legal grounding under international law. Consequently, the ruling is a decisive precedent that supports the U.S.-led freedom-of-navigation principles and undermines China’s broader territorial claims.",
